instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is validated through a continuous comparison between reference values measured on the physical test rig and the simulated outputs of the analog plant model. The following process is followed:\n\n1. **Reference acquisition**: Encoder positions and current sensor readings are saved as ground‑truth traces over a predefined test sequence (20 s ramp, 3 °/s, 30 % duty‑cycle).\n2. **Simulation**: The same set‑point sequence is injected into the Simulink animated model, producing simulated joint positions and currents.\n3. **Comparison**: Root‑mean‑square error (RMSE) and maximum‑deviation metrics are computed in real time. A tolerance band of ±0.2 % of full‑scale for position and ±1 % for current is acceptable; deviations beyond this band trigger a fault flag.\n4. **Uncertainty quantification**: Encoder quantisation error (51.2 µrad), machine back‑EMF noise (±0.5 V rms), and thermal drift (0.5 °C / °m/s²) are modelled as Gaussian perturbations in the simulation and propagated through a Monte‑Carlo study to obtain confidence intervals.\n5. **Error detection and correction**: Once a divergence is detected, the FT compares the deviation against the model’s identified sensitivity matrix; in case of consistent bias, the model parameters (stiffness, damping) are automatically re‑optimised via a least‑squares routine.\n6. **Quality assurance**: All simulation traces, comparison reports, and identified model parameter updates are version‑controlled in GitLab and subject to a peer review workflow. The DT’s verification report is generated as a PDF on daily basis and stored in the project repository."
]
